j$). Eq. (13) indicates that the maximum processing capacity of the selected distribution center can meet the total demand of all outlets. Eq. (14) ensures that only the selected distribution centers can allocate express parcels for processing. Eq. (15) specifies that the demand of each outlet is served by only one distribution center. Eq. (16) ensures that all delivery quantities are non-negative, which conforms to practical operation requirements, and ensures that the sum of weight coefficients of all distribution hubs is 1 , thereby ensuring the consistency and rationality of the model. Finally, in order to further reduce empty driving and ineffective transportation, it is required that a certain proportion of vehicles in the transportation capacity of each distribution hub must operate with full load as much as possible. These formulas jointly ensure the efficient operation and cost control of the delivery network.

